title: Update Attention operator for GPT2
body:
**Description**: 

Add unidirectional attribute for GPT2. 

The mask is with shape (S, S), where S is the sequence length. Only lower triangle will be used like
[[1, 0, 0]
 [1, 1, 0]
 [1, 1, 1]]
In cuda operator, only the first i elements are used in softmax calculation (the remaining elments will get 0.0 after softmax). num_valid for i-th row is i.

In cpu operator, the upper triangle of mask matrix is filled with -10000 like the following:
[[0, -10000, -10000],
 [0,   0,        -10000]
 [0,    0         0        ]]
It is added to GEMM result so that the elements with -10000 will get 0.0 after softmax.
When mask is unidirectional, mask_index shall not be in input.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

The mask in GPT2 is unidirectional (left-to-right): Current word can only attend to previous words on the left. Add this change to support GPT2 model.

title: Always call cudaSetDevice at the beginning of session::Run
body:
**Description**: This is required for running multithreaded with multi-GPUs. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Without it, when running in a work thread it would default to GPU 0, while CUDAExecutionProvider is assigned on other GPUs. That might cause CUDA crash when some CUDA resources is from GPU 0, while being used in GPU N>0.

```
Installing cmake 
Downloading https://github.com/Kitware/CMake/releases/download/v3.13.5/cmake-3.13.5.tar.gz
```

title: Python onnxruntime.seed(<seed>) API for random seed
body:
**Description**:
1. Add a Python API `onnxruntime.seed(<seed>)` for specifying the random seed.
_Note:  I didn't update every kernel to use this, just Dropout._  

2. Improve consistency/repeatability of Python training unit tests.

**Motivation and Context**
Add a Python API for specifying the random seed to onnxruntime, to match other frameworks, e.g.
`numpy.random.seed(<seed>)`
`torch.manual_seed(<seed>) / torch.cuda.manual_seed(<seed>)`

The `ort_trainer.py` was generating random samples directly on CUDA.  CUDA does not guarantee the same random sequence gets generated on different devices (even with the same seed).  Instead, we will generate the random sequence on CPU and move it to the device.

title: Fork the WinML APIs into the Microsoft namespace
body:
Issues: The current WinML redist implementation is under the Windows namespace. This collides with the Windows namespace in the Inbox SDK, causing developers to do activation hooking, and include path shenanigans. 

Fix: Fork the WinML APIs into the Microsoft namespace. These APIs will be kept in sync with the Windows namespace, but will not collide with the inbox sdk implementation headers/metadata.

1.	Add CMake flag to enable Microsoft namespace, onnxruntime_BUILD_WINML_IN_MICROSOFT_NS. The Default value is OFF in CMake, but is set to ON in build.py. This has the effect of all ORT builds to build into Microsoft, and inbox WinML to build into Windows by default.
2.	Update idl files with macro to toggle namespace.
3.	Build raw headers from midl with /ns_prefix for Microsoft. Redist build, and without for Windows. Inbox build. This is because we ship the raw headers in the SDK and should not generate ns_prefix.
4.	Need to organize namespacealiases combine winrt::Microsoft::* and winrt::Windows::*
5.	Need to remove all usage of winrt::Windows in favor of namespace aliases (or macros in some cases) in implementation.
6.	Need to rename the dll to Microsoft.* in redist builds.
7.	Need to remove all usage of winrt::Windows in favor of namespace aliases (or macros in some cases) in tests.
8.	Need to update nuget package to reference dll, libs, pdbs, metadata and headers with Microsoft.* and not Windows*.
9.	Need to update nuget package to include dualapipartition.h.

title: Add int64 input type for ReduceProd
body:
**Description**:
Adding int64 input type for ReduceProd

**Motivation and Context**
This input type is required for exporting numel op.
Numel op applies ReduceProd on the output of the Shape node. Output of the Shape node is always of type int64, which is expected since it represents sizes.

Numel is a frequently used operator that's used in torchvision models Mask RCNN and Keypoint RCNN.

title: Fix crash in DequantizeLinear with scalar tensor
body:
**Description**: This fixes the crash describe in #3417 where a scalar tensor crashes in the DequantizeLinear kernel.

**Motivation and Context**
The kernel for DequantizeLinear is shared between the official ONNX definition of the operator and an older contrib op version that supported an axis attribute with some broadcasting semantics. The crash was caused by not checking if the axis value as valid to use. The model from #3417 is now able to load and run and additional unit tests were added for the scalar case.

Also cleaned up the kernel registration to use the type constraints instead of explicitly listing parameter names in order to reduce code size.

title: Support override of free dimensions by name
body:
This enables sizes of free dimensions to be specified by name while a session is created, in addition to denotation.  

The existing API which is based on denotation is preserved with binary compatibility (though renamed to AddFreeDimensionOverride*ByDenotation*) and is still used by Winml.   A new API named AddFreeDimensionOverride*ByName*) is added.

This adds an EP method OnSessionInitializationEnd, similar to OnRunEnd.  The DML EP uses this method to sync and trim resources used to upload weights.

title: Dropout kernel and function body expansion updates.
body:
The change addresses two issues:

- **Function body**
  - This change enables the handling of function bodies that require function proto context in ORT by creating function body at Node Verification stage.
  - Fixes bugs around function body expansion that were causing segmentation faults and index out of bound exceptions.
  - Adds tests for NegativeLikelihoodLoss forward kernel (defined by function). 

- **Dropout-12 kernel**
  - Pursuant to https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2725 this PR introduces `training_mode` input to Dropout-12 kernel to repurpose this kernel for both inferencing and training without breaking the existing inferencing behavior where default probability is zero. The motivation for the change was to change the spec's default probability to 0.5 to make it inline with PyTorch, TensorFlow and ONNX Runtime Training.
  - Updates ORT-ONNX test infrastructure to handle dropout tests by counting the number of zeros in the output as opposed to doing absolute comparisions which will _almost_ never match because mask generated by ORT will be different from that of ONNX model baseline (generated by python based reference implementation that use np.random distribution) 
  - Separates out TrainableDropout because existing models using it will pass `training_mode` input and instead will expect it to be used for training directly. 


Please note CI builds are failing due to below tests not passing but I believe these failures are **not** related to my change, please review with confidence:

- ParallelExecutor.TestStatusPropagation
- ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTests/ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTest.TestNullInterOpThreadPool/0, where GetParam() = 1
- ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTests/ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTest.TestNullInterOpThreadPool/1, where GetParam() = 0

**Description**:
Version update for OpenVINO Execution Provider. Based on the latest OpenVINO release 2020.2 which now includes nGraph stack. Model conversion from ONNX to OpenVINO IR is now done using nGraph ONNX importer component.

- Supports models with symbolic dimensions in shapes.
- Uses OpenVINO APIs with Long Term Support (LTS) providing extended support and backward compatibility.
- Upto 40% reduction in memory footprint.
- Avoids using the python components used by existing version EP thus avoiding expensive python interpreter startup and module conflicts arising from it.

title: Fork WinML IDL Guids
body:
Issue: WinML interfaces share the same guids as the inbox distribution of WinML.
Sharing these guids cause the component to fail WACK compliance, as Inbox SDK component IDs cannot be reused by out-of-the-box components.

To support the component in Store apps in the future, we do not want to change the guids, and introduce a possible breaking change to client apps.

Fix: Fork the GUIDs that define the WinML interfaces to be unique across the Microsoft and Windows namespaces.
